# Raw agentic AI repos that teach you the real patterns

**You don't need a framework to build agents.** The most educational GitHub repositories for agentic AI strip away LangChain, MCP, and AutoGen to reveal a surprisingly simple core: an LLM in a loop, calling functions, passing results back. The 14 repos below — spanning Python, Rust, Go, JavaScript, and Bash — demonstrate every major agentic pattern using only native code and direct API calls. Anthropic's own cookbook is the single best starting point, with reference implementations of six foundational patterns in pure SDK calls.

---

## Anthropic's cookbook is the canonical starting point

**[anthropics/anthropic-cookbook](https://github.com/anthropics/anthropic-cookbook)** — Python, Anthropic Claude — ⭐ ~32k

This is the definitive resource. The `patterns/agents/` directory contains reference implementations from Anthropic's landmark "Building Effective Agents" blog post by Erik Schluntz and Barry Zhang. It covers **six distinct patterns**: prompt chaining (sequential LLM calls where each uses prior output), routing (classifying input to specialized handlers), orchestrator-workers (a central LLM dynamically delegating to worker LLMs), parallelization (simultaneous LLM calls), evaluator-optimizer (iterative refinement loops), and simple autonomous agents (LLMs using tools in a feedback loop). Every example uses only the `anthropic` Python SDK — a `util.py` with helpers for authentication and a raw `client.messages.create()` call driving each pattern. Self-contained notebooks with detailed comments explain the *why* behind every design choice. **If you read one repo on this list, make it this one.**

**[anthropics/claude-quickstarts](https://github.com/anthropics/claude-quickstarts)** (computer-use-demo/) — Python, Anthropic Claude — ⭐ ~14k

The `computer-use-demo/computer_use_demo/loop.py` file is the **purest agent loop in existence**: roughly 200 lines that call the Claude API, check for `tool_use` stop reasons, execute tools locally (bash, mouse/keyboard, text editor), append results to context, and repeat. No orchestration framework — just a `while` loop and the Anthropic SDK. This is the official reference implementation for Claude's computer use capability, and it demonstrates how autonomous task-solving agents actually work at the API level.

