## OpenAI's Swarm distills multi-agent orchestration to its essence

**[openai/swarm](https://github.com/openai/swarm)** — Python, OpenAI — ⭐ ~21k

OpenAI's educational framework reduces multi-agent systems to **two primitives**: an `Agent` (instructions + functions) and **handoffs** (returning another Agent from a function call). The entire core orchestration loop in `swarm/core.py` is roughly **100 lines**: get completion → execute tool calls → switch agent if a handoff occurred → update context → repeat. It ships with five worked examples — airline customer service (flight changes, cancellations, baggage across multiple specialized agents), a triage router, a personal shopper, and a support bot with UI and help-center agents. Swarm proves that multi-agent coordination is fundamentally just function calling plus conversation routing. Now superseded by the OpenAI Agents SDK for production, it remains the clearest educational implementation of the handoff pattern.

**[openai/openai-cookbook](https://github.com/openai/openai-cookbook)** (Orchestrating_agents.ipynb) — Python, OpenAI — ⭐ ~72k

The `Orchestrating_agents.ipynb` notebook is the theoretical blueprint that became Swarm. It builds the entire agent loop from scratch in approximately **50 lines of Python**: define "routines" (system prompt + tools), implement `run_full_turn()`, and wire up agent handoffs via `transfer_to_XXX` functions. The function calling notebooks (`How_to_call_functions_with_chat_models.ipynb`) show the fundamental building block — defining JSON schemas, parsing `tool_calls`, executing functions, returning results — with zero abstractions beyond `client.chat.completions.create()`.

