## Three repos under 100 lines that rival full frameworks

**[SWE-agent/mini-swe-agent](https://github.com/SWE-agent/mini-swe-agent)** — Python, any LLM via LiteLLM — ⭐ ~3.2k

Built by the Princeton and Stanford team behind SWE-bench, this is approximately **100 lines of Python** for the core agent class. It uses **only bash as its tool** — no function-calling API needed. Actions execute via `subprocess.run()`, and every action is completely independent. Despite this radical simplicity, it achieves over **74% on SWE-bench Verified**, rivaling systems with thousands of lines of code. The insight: agents are fundamentally "LLM + loop + shell." Used in production by Meta, NVIDIA, and IBM.

**[The-Pocket/PocketFlow](https://github.com/The-Pocket/PocketFlow)** — Python (also TS, Java, Go, Rust, C++) — ⭐ ~10k+

The entire framework is exactly **100 lines of code** with zero dependencies. The core abstraction is a directed graph: `Node` objects with `prep()`/`exec()`/`post()` lifecycle methods connected by labeled edges, communicating via a shared store. From this single primitive, the documentation shows how to implement agents, RAG, map-reduce, task decomposition, and multi-agent workflows. Created by a Microsoft Research AI Frontiers researcher, PocketFlow proves that **all LLM framework patterns reduce to a graph plus shared state**. Ports in seven languages demonstrate the abstraction is universal.

**[Antropath/minimal-agent](https://github.com/Antropath/minimal-agent)** — Python, any LLM via LiteLLM — ⭐ ~89

The core `agents.py` is roughly **100 lines** (excluding comments) implementing the ReAct pattern: the agent reasons, writes Python code as actions, executes it, observes results, and repeats. Extensively commented for education, with an architecture diagram included. Inspired by HuggingFace's smolagents but built entirely from scratch. This is the best-documented educational implementation of the **Reason + Act loop** available.

