## Tool use without the abstraction layers

**[AbanteAI/rawdog](https://github.com/AbanteAI/rawdog)** — Python, any LLM via LiteLLM — ⭐ ~1.8k

Rawdog takes a fundamentally different approach to tool use: instead of function calling, the LLM generates complete Python scripts that are **auto-executed via `exec()`**. The output is appended to conversation context, enabling the model to self-select context by printing values, reading its own output, and iterating. The name stands for "Recursive Augmentation With Deterministic Output Generations." A `--leash` mode requires manual approval before execution. This repo demonstrates that tool use doesn't require a formal function-calling API — **code generation itself is the universal tool**.

**[sigoden/aichat](https://github.com/sigoden/aichat)** — Rust, 20+ providers — ⭐ ~9.3k

A single Rust binary providing shell assistance, chat REPL, RAG, and AI agents with tool calling — all via **native code, no Python, no frameworks**. The companion repo `sigoden/llm-functions` lets you write tools as plain Bash, JavaScript, or Python functions with a simple naming convention. The formula is explicit: `AI Agent = Instructions (Prompt) + Tools (Function Callings) + Documents (RAG)`. This is the best example of building a production-grade CLI agent in a systems language.

**[danielmiessler/fabric](https://github.com/danielmiessler/fabric)** — Go, OpenAI/Claude/Ollama — ⭐ ~30k+

Fabric demonstrates a **Unix-native approach** to agentic workflows. Prompts are Markdown files in a `/patterns` directory; you compose them via Unix pipes: `echo "idea" | fabric --pattern write_essay | to_pdf`. Each pattern is a system prompt, and helper tools (`yt` for YouTube transcripts, `to_pdf` for conversion) are separate Go binaries. This is "tool use" at the shell level — **the pipe is the orchestrator**. No agent loop needed; the filesystem and Unix philosophy replace the framework.

