## Multi-agent debate shows coordination without a coordinator

**[composable-models/llm_multiagent_debate](https://github.com/composable-models/llm_multiagent_debate)** — Python, OpenAI — ⭐ ~510

This ICML 2024 paper implementation puts **three LLM agents** through multi-round debate: each generates an independent response, then all responses are shared across agents, who refine their answers based on others' reasoning. Each task (math, GSM8K, biographies, MMLU) is a single script using **direct OpenAI API calls** with zero framework overhead. The results show that more agents and more debate rounds consistently improve factuality and reasoning. This repo demonstrates multi-agent coordination through the simplest possible mechanism — structured message passing.

**[victordibia/designing-multiagent-systems](https://github.com/victordibia/designing-multiagent-systems)** — Python, OpenAI/Azure — ⭐ ~296

The companion repo to the book "Designing Multi-Agent Systems" includes a from-scratch framework called **PicoAgents** with 50+ runnable examples. It covers round-robin orchestration, AI-driven speaker selection, plan-based orchestration (Magentic One style), sequential and parallel workflows, evaluator-optimizer loops, and DAG-based execution. Every pattern is implemented transparently. The repo also includes equivalent implementations in LangGraph and AutoGen for comparison, making it uniquely valuable for understanding **what frameworks actually do under the hood**.

